Tacoma Portside Watershed Pollution Uptake - 2014

Below is an index which seeks to estimate the degree to which watersheds and watershed segments in the vicinity of the port of Tacoma absorb pollutants from 2014 toxic release facilities, automotive traffic, and shipping activities based on 2020 LIDAR point cloud data. Watersheds were identified through the use of hydrology tools in QGIS. All relevant pollution sources were given one mile buffer zones, which were used to identify the average number of such polluting sites in range of any given part of a given watershed, which enabled the classification of watersheds as likely receiving a particularly high or low pollutant input from a given source and thus the overall ranking of the watersheds.

This should not be taken in any sense as definitive or authoritative. Not only are many of the watersheds identified blatantly roadways (though given the impact of impervious surfaces, perhaps their identification as drainage channels is not so wrong as it might first seem) and many of the actual watersheds of the area not generated at all, but this is only a small sampling of the number of possible predictor variables, weighted arbitrarily based on the maker's own judgement rather than by any statistically validated means. The use of modern roadway networks (though not so much modern LIDAR data) may also have created some inaccuracies when matched with 2014 toxic release data.
